            "Nuclear",
            "Nuclear power"
          ],
          "hint": "This method does not burn fossil fuels but still creates steam.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP3"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What term is used for organic materials, such as wood pellets, burned to generate power?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Biomass"
          ],
          "hint": "This involves burning plant-based or organic waste.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP5"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which large-scale renewable method relies on falling water to turn turbines?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Hydro",
            "Hydroelectric"
          ],
          "hint": "This uses the movement of water from a height.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP4"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How do fossil fuel and nuclear power stations share the same basic mechanical process for generating electricity?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Both use heat to create steam",
        "Steam is used to turn turbines",
        "Turbines drive the generators",
        "Both rely on thermal energy conversion"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP2",
        "TP3"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about what actually turns the turbines in both types of stations."
    },
    {
      "title": "Micro-Generation and Local Supply",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the technical name for the solar panel systems used in micro-generation?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Photovoltaic",
            "PV"
          ],
          "hint": "It is often abbreviated to two letters.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Where is micro-generation electricity produced in relation to the end user?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Point of consumption",
            "Locally",
            "At the home or office"
          ],
          "hint": "It is produced exactly where it is needed.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Why are most micro-generation systems still connected to the National Grid?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "To export excess power",
            "To import power when needed",
            "Grid backup"
          ],
          "hint": "Think about what happens when the sun isn't shining or when too much power is made.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP5"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How does micro-generation fundamentally change the path electricity takes compared to large-scale generation?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "It removes the need for long-distance transmission",
        "Electricity is produced at the point of use",
        "It reduces reliance on central power stations",
        "The consumer becomes a producer"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP1",
        "TP4"
      ],
      "hint": "Compare where the power is made versus where it is used in both systems."
    },
    {
      "title": "The Purpose of High Voltage Transmission",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the technical term for the energy lost as heat when current flows through a cable's resistance?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "I²R loss",
            "I2R loss"
          ],
          "hint": "It is a formula representing heat loss.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP1"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What happens to the current level when voltage is stepped up for transmission?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Decreases",
            "Lower current",
            "Reduces"
          ],
          "hint": "High voltage results in the opposite for current.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP2"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which component is used at power stations to increase the voltage for the transmission network?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Transformer",
            "Step-up transformer"
          ],
          "hint": "This device changes voltage levels.",
          "sourceTeachingPointIds": [
            "TP5"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why does increasing the transmission voltage allow for the use of cables with a smaller cross-sectional area?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Higher voltage reduces the current",
        "Lower current produces less heat",
        "Thinner cables can safely carry lower current",
        "Reduces the weight and cost of the cables"
      ],
      "deeperSourceTeachingPointIds": [
        "TP2",
        "TP3",
        "TP4"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the relationship between current, heat, and the size of the conductor needed."
    }
  ]
}

{
